// PARSING AND PROJECT FOUNDATION
I started by setting up the core parsing infrastructure, building the OSM parser and organising the package
structure so the project had a solid foundation to build on.

// INITIAL RENDERING
Early on I also did most of the initial rendering work for Bornholm, which involved getting the coastline fill
working correctly, filtering out ferry routes, adding colour mapping for different OSM tags like farmland and
water, and making sure larger polygons like land and sea rendered before smaller details so nothing got covered up.

// HEIGHT CURVE PARSER
From there I built the height curve parser, which required handling the parent-child tree structure of nested
contour lines. I then wired this into the renderer and worked on the colour logic so elevation bands were
visually readable. This part took a fair amount of iteration to get right.

// BINARY SERIALIZATION
I also implemented binary serialization, meaning the app serializes the parsed map data to a binary file after
the first load so subsequent launches skip parsing entirely and start up much faster. I added the startup dialog
that lets the user choose which map to load as part of this.

// TESTING
On the testing side I built out the parser test suite, the height curve tests, and later added tests for
BoundingBox, ShapeBuilder and AdaptivePath. I also wrote the DependsOn extension to stop cascading test
failures from obscuring the real cause of a breakage.

// PERFORMANCE AND RENDERING OPTIMIZATIONS
Towards the end of the project I focused heavily on performance. I implemented the Ramer-Douglas-Peucker line
simplification algorithm and the LodAssigner class which controls at what zoom level each type of road or
feature becomes visible.

I then did a round of rendering optimizations including adding a dirty flag so the app only redraws when
something has actually changed, caching stroke objects and height curve paths to avoid rebuilding them every
frame, and reusing a single image buffer instead of allocating a new one each render cycle.

// DOCUMENTATION
Finally I did a full JavaDoc pass across the core classes.